metadata.name: sandspiral II #152
metadata.description: This is a re-imagining of my new forms 04: sand spirals mint from hic et nunc in April '21. (https://hen.hicathon.xyz/objkt/68268 ). It has been altered to produce unique mints. There are 12 different random traits seeded from the operation hash, but only four are visible: primary hue, secondary hue, initial rotation, and line width. All values are equal likelihood, so there is no "rarity" per se; aesthetic value is the only trait that matters.

metadata.name: Turbulence #398
metadata.description:
Swirly shapes are rendered by passes of poisson samples of a warped noise field. The noise shifts with each pass, creating a layered effect. 

Dense editions may take over 2 minutes to draw fully.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume at any time during the drawing.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a not 1:1 variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

Common:
- 43 set palettes plus many more with combinations
- 3 color distribution methods
- 50/50 dark
- 50/50 monochrome with bright highlights 
- 3 drawing styles: lines, points, colored pencils
- 5 noises effects: full screen, distance from center, distance from bottom, horizontal center, vertical center, random circles, 3,5, or 7 horizontal and vertical bars
- Poisson point distribution based on set layers or the noise value

Rare
- 15% chance of a dark monochrome with gold strands

Copyright (c) 2022 Matt Perkins, hello@mattperkins.me, @nudoru on Twitter. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: DEGREES OF FREEDOM #16
metadata.description:
Forms constricted to a plane, yearning to be free. Multitudes of expression, endless possibilities of shapes, the inevitable hissing rising from the dreaded empty page.

This piece is inspired by the Futurists' concept of 'universal dynamism' - the idea that separations between objects and their contexts are an illusion and time makes any distinctions meaningless. It tries to capture the expressivity of the moving object along all its potential vectors.

This piece evolved from my #genuary piece for 'Minimalism' (which was even then more surrealism than anything else). DEGREES OF FREEDOM is minted as part of #genuary32nd.

Press 'S' to take a screenshot. Recommended resolution: 2400 x 3000 pixels.
Written in JavaScript without libraries, February 2023.

metadata.name: Stacking I - Genuary Edition #27
metadata.description:
This year's Genuary has been so much fun and alongside, I have been working on making my "Stacking" collection generative. 

The Genuary32 event is the ideal time to showcase what I have produced. 
This is the first in a series of five Stacking Tokens.

Features:
8 Different color palettes including 4 taken from the Studio Yorktown Color Town Hall:
Benelit - Esquisse - Maneki - Stockholm Lollipop (Studio Yorktown)
Jasmin - Retro - Neon - St Kilda (P1xelboy)

5 Different configurations:
Centred Tower
Duo Grid
Trio Grid
Left Hand Tower
Right Hand Tower

Made in P5.js by P1xelboy - February 2023
Special thanks to Studio Yorktown for creating the Color Townhall.

metadata.name: Sketch F #555
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch F(ree). A gift to all Sketch A-E collectors. The underlying grid structure from A-E remains, but more variation on size and distribution is added. Many more color palettes are introduced. Grid size, padding, and colors vary.

metadata.name: Planetarium #163
metadata.description:
Francesco Forcellini, November 2022, Milano, Italy.
Compositions of spheres made with grids, proportions, symmetries and  broken symmetries,  order and casualties.


To save an image with the size of the window press S once the image is fully rendered.
To save a Hi-Resolution image 6000px x 8000px press H and wait, the page will reload and start to render.


Published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.
Built using p5js,a custom WEBGL shader and a shader with a modified version of "cnoise" by Stefan Gustavson.
See the License.md for license details.

metadata.name: Reverie #49
metadata.description:
Reverie: a state of being pleasantly lost in one's thoughts; a daydream.

I love impressionist paintings of nature, where the visible brushstrokes give a glimpse into the artist’s process. With this collection I aimed to capture a slice of nature with distinctly digital “brushstrokes”. Looking closely, you can see many of the lines, curves and polygons that combined to form each Reverie. 

Keyboard Interactions:
[z] Change color / season. There are two seasons, winter and not-winter. Weather (wind, ice) is as unpredictable as it is in nature.
[p] Play / pause. Automatically cycle through colors and seasons.
[s] Save 1000x1000px image (instant)
[2] Save 2000x2000px image (fast)
[4] Save 4000x4000px image (slowish)


Elsif 2022, made with p5js.

metadata.name: Annihilate This Week #65
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to "Saturday Night's Alright (For Fighting)" (project #14045). Same algorithm of the previous one, only slightly modified, the main difference is that here the daily variations are all mixed up together and the output doesn't change based on the current day.

This is intended to be a gift for all collectors and the community of fx(hash) that showed so much support for the "Saturday" project, really beyond my expectations.

50% of the royalties goes to the minter, do with the piece whatever you'd like, hold it, sell or trade it, or even burn it if you really don't like it :)

Thank you!

----

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Cosmic reaction #7
metadata.description:
As per my daily programming routine, this time I went to combine different circle algorithms, like my last work. This work, by using the optimized algorithm of packing and fields and combining them with a pattern for the inner connection of the circles, presents an artwork with high details that can be seen in large dimensions by plotting it. There are different variations, some of which are more detailed. The colors of some circles, at much higher resolutions, may look very slightly different.
_________________________

To see the artwork in high quality, open it in live view and add “&res=1 to 25” to the URL, This artwork can also be plotted in large dimensions.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #2
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Inefficient Ways of Independence #30
metadata.description:
"Inefficient Ways of Independence" is a thought - provoking artwork that explores the relationship between technology and the human experience.

The piece features a collection of iconic symbols of old technology, such as closed - circuit TV cameras, floppy disks, and vintage Mac computers, coupled together by a flow of particles.

The use of human body parts or heads adds a personal touch to the work, highlighting the intimate connection between the individual and technology.

The title "Inefficient Ways of Independence" serves as a commentary on our dependence on technology and the way that it has changed over time.

It also raises questions about our relationship with technology and the limitations that it can impose.

The piece invites the viewer to consider how technology has shaped our lives and to reflect on the consequences of our reliance on it.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT

metadata.name: RAUSCH #130
metadata.description:
RAUSCH is a series of generative artworks that explore imaginary digital architectures. 

This series challenges traditional notions of architectural representation and raises important questions about the role of resolution in design. Just as the pixel resolution of an image affects its perceived quality, the resolution of an architectural space can affect its qualities and livability. By embracing digital variation through codes, this series explores the interplay between abstract and concrete space through multiple resolutions. 

RAUSCH is inspired by the feeling of being overwhelmed by complex, chaotic and messy sensations, and aims to engage the viewer through a sense of wonder, disorientation, and awe.

Released on the occasion of Companions of Code, a group exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art at The NFT Gallery in London. 
Curated by Micol Ap. Exhibition 10-24 February 2023 

___________________________________________________
RAUSCH Controls:

Animation: 
• ‘1 - 2 - 3 - 4’ animate views
• 'MouseClick' pause/play animation

Functions:
(press key & wait)
• 'F' 24 FPS
• 'B' b/w mode 

Resize Canvas:
(press key & wait)
• '6' Portrait A4 - 1000x1414
• '7' Landscape 16:9 - 1920x1080
• '8' Portrait 9:16 - 1080x1920
• '9' Square 1:1 - 1024x1024
• 'DoubleClick' Fullscreen

Save & Export Image:
• 'S' save a .png of in current resolution

Save & Export GIF:
• 'G' save a 1-2 sec. seamless loop .gif of current view 
• 'P' save a 12-24 sec. seamless loop .gif of all the views
• 'T’ scale down current resolution, save a 12 sec. seamless loop .gif

Steps to save a gif/png :
• go in live/open mode (wait)
• resize canvas with 6,7,8, or 9 to your desired aspect ratio (wait)
• press S,G or P to save & download (wait) 
• enjoy RAUSCH :)

Save & Export GIF for social media sharing:
• go in live/open mode (wait)
• press T or G wait for recalculation & download. 
• enjoy RAUSCH 
• post on Twitter ;)
__________________________________________________

This token may not work on mobile(!), but it allows exporting .png and .gif (see controls) to enjoy RAUSCH on different displays or mobile. Tested on Mozilla, Chrome, Safari. Created with P5js & p5.createLoop

RAUSCH Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2023

metadata.name: When we were Kids #60
metadata.description:
When we were kids.

A work that goes back to our childhood.
When I was a kid I loved spending time with my grandmother and parents, we took a lot of walks with them, looked at different houses, spent time in nature, painted and in general were very much involved in the creative component, it was my parents and grandmother who instilled in me a love for creativity.

Probably one of the few things that have survived to these days is my childhood drawings, a little funny, sloppy, but so real and sincere.

In this work I wanted to take me back to those carefree times and remember with what eagerness and zeal I tried every day to learn something new or to go further than before.

None of this would have happened without my family, for which I am truly grateful.

10% of primary sales will be donated to Cure Parkinson's, I hope all children will have a childhood where they can spend time with their loved ones.

Be patient, some variations take a little longer to render.

Press S for Save Canvas as PNG.

By aleks.ustya, @ALEKUSTN. Made with p5js.
